04281nam a22006615i 9780231549301DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019008054  a97802315493017 a10.7312/zhu-191242doi  a(DE-B1597)544824  a(OCoLC)1132359035  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL2464.Z6bZ5814613 2020 7aLIT0080102bisacsh1 aZhu, Xi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Original Meaning of the Yijing :bCommentary on the Scripture of Change /cXi Zhu. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b24 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTranslations from the Asian Classics00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The “Original Meaning” of the Zhou Changes (Zhouyi benyih) -- tZhouyi benyi -- t1. Part A: Hexagrams 1– 30 -- t2. Part B: Hexagrams 31– 64 -- t3. Treatise on the Appended Remarks (Xici zhuan) -- t4. Treatise Discussing the Trigrams (Shuogua zhuan) -- t5. Commentary on Assorted Hexagrams (Zagua zhuan) -- tAppendix: Divination Ritual (Shiyi) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Yijing (I Ching), or Scripture of Change, is traditionally considered the first and most profound of the Chinese classics. Originally a divination manual based on trigrams and hexagrams, by the beginning of the first millennium it had acquired written explanations and a series of appendices attributed to Confucius, which transformed it into a work of wisdom literature as well as divination. Over the centuries, hundreds of commentaries were written on it, but for the past thousand years, one of the most influential has been that of Zhu Xi (1130–1200), who synthesized the major interpretive approaches to the text and integrated it into his system of moral self-cultivation.Joseph A. Adler’s translation of the Yijing includes for the first time in any Western language Zhu Xi’s commentary in full. Adler explores Zhu Xi’s interpretation of the text and situates it in the context of his overall theoretical system. Zhu Xi held that the Yijing was originally composed for the purpose of divination by the mythic sage Fuxi, who intended to create a system to aid decision making. The text’s meaning, therefore, could not be captured by a single commentator; it would emerge for each person through the process of divination. This translation makes available to the English-language audience a crucial text in the history of Chinese religion and philosophy, with an introduction and translator’s notes that explain its intellectual and historical context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aBook of Changes.  aChu Hsi.  aClassic of Changes.  aI Ching.  aMaster Chu.  aShuogua.  aYijing.  aZagua.  aZhouyi.  aZhu Xi.  adivination.  ahexagram.  atrigrams.1 aAdler, Joseph.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195940uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/zhu-1912440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231549301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231549301.jpg  a978-3-11-065195-9  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles